│ the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes with a SIGSEGV while computing the    │
│ cost of widening a call to the intrinsic llvm.powi.* during vectorization     │
│ planning. The stack trace shows the crash occurs inside                       │
│ BasicTTIImplBase<AArch64TTIImpl>::getIntrinsicInstrCost(), specifically when  │
│ dereferencing I->getParent()->getParent() (frame #7/#5 in the trace). This    │
│ indicates a null pointer dereference of the intrinsic instruction             │
│ pointer.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe first transformation point reported  │
│ is TargetTransformInfo::Model<...>::getIntrinsicInstrCost(). That aligns with │
│ VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost building IntrinsicCostAttributes and querying  │
│ TTI for the intrinsic cost. In VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost we construct    │
│ IntrinsicCostAttributes using the constructor that does NOT pass an           │
│ IntrinsicInst*, so ICA.getInst() returns nullptr. The cost model then calls   │
│ AArch64TTIImpl::getIntrinsicInstrCost(), which forwards to the base           │
│ implementation in BasicTTIImpl.h. Inside the switch handling Intrinsic::powi, │
│ it unconditionally dereferences I (the result of ICA.getInst()) to query      │
│ optimization-for-size, leading to the segfault.\n\n3. Root Cause              │
│ Analysis:\nIn BasicTTIImpl::getIntrinsicInstrCost (lines around 1567-1575),   │
│ the code assumes ICA.getInst() is non-null for Intrinsic::powi. However,      │
│ callers like VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost intentionally create              │
│ IntrinsicCostAttributes without an underlying IR instruction when computing   │
│ hypothetical vector forms (using only types and argument values). Thus I is   │
│ null and dereferencing it causes a crash. This is a missing null check. Other │
│ intrinsic cases in the same function either avoid dereferencing I or guard    │
│ its usage, but powi does not.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nEdit file       │
│ llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/BasicTTIImpl.h at line 1572.\nChange the line:\n    │
│ bool ShouldOptForSize = I->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();\nTo safely │
│ handle a null intrinsic instruction pointer:\n  bool ShouldOptForSize = I &&  │
│ I->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();\nOptionally expanded form:\n  bool │
│ ShouldOptForSize = false;\n  if (I)\n    ShouldOptForSize =                   │
│ I->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();\nA single-line replacement with    │
│ the short-circuit is sufficient and minimally invasive.\nRationale: When I is │
│ null (type-based cost query), we conservatively assume size is not being      │
│ optimized. This preserves existing behavior for real instructions while       │
│ preventing the crash.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nAdding a null check around the use   │
│ of I in the powi intrinsic cost computation prevents a null dereference       │
│ during vectorization cost modeling when the intrinsic instruction pointer is  │
│ absent. This resolves the segmentation fault without altering semantics for   │
│ valid instruction-based queries. Expected effect: loop-vectorizer no longer   │
│ crashes on loops containing llvm.powi; it proceeds to evaluate cost and       │
│ continue vectorization decisions normally.\n"})                               │
