│ ```                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The loop-vectorizer crashes with a SIGSEGV while computing the cost of        │
│ widening a call to the intrinsic llvm.powi.* during vectorization planning.   │
│ The stack trace shows the crash occurs inside                                 │
│ BasicTTIImplBase<AArch64TTIImpl>::getIntrinsicInstrCost(), specifically when  │
│ dereferencing I->getParent()->getParent() (frame #7/#5 in the trace). This    │
│ indicates a null pointer dereference of the intrinsic instruction pointer.    │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The first transformation point reported is                                    │
│ TargetTransformInfo::Model<...>::getIntrinsicInstrCost(). That aligns with    │
│ VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost building IntrinsicCostAttributes and querying  │
│ TTI for the intrinsic cost. In VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost we construct    │
│ IntrinsicCostAttributes using the constructor that does NOT pass an           │
│ IntrinsicInst*, so ICA.getInst() returns nullptr. The cost model then calls   │
│ AArch64TTIImpl::getIntrinsicInstrCost(), which forwards to the base           │
│ implementation in BasicTTIImpl.h. Inside the switch handling Intrinsic::powi, │
│ it unconditionally dereferences I (the result of ICA.getInst()) to query      │
│ optimization-for-size, leading to the segfault.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In BasicTTIImpl::getIntrinsicInstrCost (lines around 1567-1575), the code     │
│ assumes ICA.getInst() is non-null for Intrinsic::powi. However, callers like  │
│ VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost intentionally create IntrinsicCostAttributes   │
│ without an underlying IR instruction when computing hypothetical vector forms │
│ (using only types and argument values). Thus I is null and dereferencing it   │
│ causes a crash. This is a missing null check. Other intrinsic cases in the    │
│ same function either avoid dereferencing I or guard its usage, but powi does  │
│ not.                                                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ Edit file llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/BasicTTIImpl.h at line 1572.              │
│ Change the line:                                                              │
│   bool ShouldOptForSize = I->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();          │
│ To safely handle a null intrinsic instruction pointer:                        │
│   bool ShouldOptForSize = I && I->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();     │
│ Optionally expanded form:                                                     │
│   bool ShouldOptForSize = false;                                              │
│   if (I)                                                                      │
│     ShouldOptForSize = I->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();             │
│ A single-line replacement with the short-circuit is sufficient and minimally  │
│ invasive.                                                                     │
│ Rationale: When I is null (type-based cost query), we conservatively assume   │
│ size is not being optimized. This preserves existing behavior for real        │
│ instructions while preventing the crash.                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ Adding a null check around the use of I in the powi intrinsic cost            │
│ computation prevents a null dereference during vectorization cost modeling    │
│ when the intrinsic instruction pointer is absent. This resolves the           │
│ segmentation fault without altering semantics for valid instruction-based     │
│ queries. Expected effect: loop-vectorizer no longer crashes on loops          │
│ containing llvm.powi; it proceeds to evaluate cost and continue vectorization │
│ decisions normally.                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
